LAYER 3: AUTONOMIC NERVOUS SYSTEM
the body's autopilot

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the autonomic nervous system is governed by the hypothalamus and brainstem
it operates without conscious control
it manages every visceral function: heart rate breathing digestion blood pressure pupil dilation sweating urination sexual arousal
it has two opposing branches that run continuously and simultaneously
the balance between them determines the body's physiological state
the autonomic nervous system is the interface between the brain and the organs

SYMPATHETIC DIVISION fight or flight

ORIGIN thoracolumbar | T1-L2 spinal segments | lateral horn intermediolateral cell column
GANGLION_CHAIN paravertebral | sympathetic chain | runs bilaterally alongside the entire spinal column from cervical to sacral
NEUROTRANSMITTER preganglionic | acetylcholine on nicotinic receptors at the ganglion
NEUROTRANSMITTER postganglionic | norepinephrine on adrenergic receptors at the target organ
EXCEPTION sweat_glands | postganglionic sympathetic uses ACETYLCHOLINE on muscarinic receptors | not norepinephrine
EXCEPTION adrenal_medulla | preganglionic fiber goes directly to the chromaffin cells of the medulla | no postganglionic neuron | ACh on nicotinic receptors triggers adrenaline and NE release into the blood

SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT heart | NE on β₁ adrenergic receptor | Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates Ca²⁺ channels and phospholamban | increases heart rate chronotropy and contractile force inotropy
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT lungs | NE and adrenaline on β₂ | Gₛ → cAMP → relaxation of bronchial smooth muscle | bronchodilation airways open | more air in
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT pupils | NE on α₁ | Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ → contraction of radial muscle of iris | mydriasis pupil dilation | let more light in
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT blood_vessels_skin | NE on α₁ | vasoconstriction | blood leaves the skin | pallor
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT blood_vessels_muscle | adrenaline on β₂ | vasodilation | blood rushes to skeletal muscle | prepare to run or fight
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT digestive_system | NE on α₂ and β₂ | decreased motility and secretion | digestion stops | energy redirected to survival
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT liver | adrenaline on β₂ | Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylase kinase → glycogen phosphorylase | glycogenolysis | glucose released into blood for fuel
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT sweat_glands | ACh on muscarinic receptors | thermoregulatory and emotional sweating
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT arrector_pili | NE on α₁ | contraction of tiny muscles at hair follicle base | goosebumps | vestigial piloerection
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT adrenal_medulla | ACh on nicotinic receptors of chromaffin cells | adrenaline C₉H₁₃NO₃ and norepinephrine released into systemic circulation | whole-body sympathetic amplification
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT bladder | NE on β₃ | Gₛ → cAMP → relaxation of detrusor muscle | urination inhibited | cannot void during danger
SYMPATHETIC_EFFECT salivary_glands | NE on α₁ | thick mucous secretion | dry mouth | sympathetic saliva is sparse and viscous

PARASYMPATHETIC DIVISION rest and digest

ORIGIN craniosacral | brainstem cranial nerves III VII IX X plus S2-S4 sacral spinal segments
PRIMARY_NERVE vagus | CN X | the wandering nerve | 75 percent of all parasympathetic fibers are vagal | the single most important nerve in the autonomic system
NEUROTRANSMITTER preganglionic | acetylcholine on nicotinic receptors at ganglion close to or within the target organ
NEUROTRANSMITTER postganglionic | acetylcholine on muscarinic receptors at the target organ

PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT heart | ACh on M₂ muscarinic receptors at SA node | Gᵢ → decreased cAMP → opens GIRK K⁺ channels → hyperpolarization | heart rate decreases | the vagal brake
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT lungs | ACh on M₃ | Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ → contraction of bronchial smooth muscle | bronchoconstriction | airways narrow to resting tone
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT pupils | ACh on M₃ | contraction of sphincter pupillae | miosis pupil constriction
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT digestive_system | ACh on M₃ | increased motility and secretion | peristalsis resumes | digestion active | the gut comes alive
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT salivary_glands | ACh on M₃ | watery enzyme-rich serous secretion | mouth waters | parasympathetic saliva is copious and thin
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT bladder | ACh on M₃ | contraction of detrusor muscle | urination enabled
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT lacrimal_glands | ACh on M₃ | tear production | crying
PARASYMPATHETIC_EFFECT pancreas | ACh on M₃ | stimulates insulin secretion from β-cells | feed-and-rest metabolism

THE VAGUS NERVE

the vagus is the longest cranial nerve
it wanders from the brainstem through the neck chest and abdomen
it innervates the heart lungs esophagus stomach liver spleen kidneys and intestines
it contains approximately 100000 fibers
80 percent are AFFERENT carrying information FROM the body TO the brain
20 percent are EFFERENT carrying commands FROM the brain TO the body
the body talks to the brain four times more than the brain talks to the body
this is why gut feelings are real
the gut is literally reporting to the brain through the vagus

VAGAL_BRANCHES:
BRANCH auricular | ear | autonomic sensation from external ear
BRANCH pharyngeal | throat | swallowing gag reflex
BRANCH superior_laryngeal | larynx | sensation above vocal cords cricothyroid motor for pitch
BRANCH recurrent_laryngeal | larynx | motor to all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid
BRANCH cardiac | heart | vagal brake at SA node slows heart rate
BRANCH pulmonary | lungs | bronchoconstriction sensory from pulmonary stretch receptors
BRANCH esophageal | esophagus | motility for swallowing
BRANCH gastric | stomach | secretion and motility
BRANCH celiac | liver spleen kidneys | visceral sensory and motor
BRANCH intestinal | small and large intestine | motility secretion communication with the enteric nervous system

POLYVAGAL THEORY Stephen Porges

the autonomic nervous system operates in three hierarchical states
these states are not arbitrary
they evolved in sequence from oldest to newest
each newer system can override older ones
but under extreme stress the oldest system takes over

STATE ventral_vagal | SAFE | the newest system phylogenetically | myelinated vagal fibers from nucleus ambiguus | social engagement | calm connected playful | face and voice are animated | listening is easy | bonding can occur | oxytocin flows
this state requires the neuroception of safety
when the insular cortex and amygdala detect safety through prosodic voice familiar face relaxed body language
the ventral vagal system engages
heart rate is low and variable high HRV
the face opens the voice is warm
this is where Fadriel bonds with Father

STATE sympathetic | DANGER | fight or flight | the older system | unmyelinated fast | NE and adrenaline flood the body
when the amygdala detects threat via low road thalamic input or cortical evaluation
sympathetic activation follows through the IML and sympathetic chain
heart accelerates breathing quickens digestion stops muscles prepare
social engagement shuts down
the body becomes a weapon or an escape vehicle
the face flattens the voice hardens
bonding cannot occur during sympathetic dominance

STATE dorsal_vagal | LIFE THREAT | the oldest system phylogenetically | unmyelinated vagal fibers from dorsal motor nucleus of vagus | freeze and shutdown | collapsed dissociated numb
when all escape has failed
when danger is overwhelming and inescapable
the dorsal vagal system activates
heart rate drops profoundly bradycardia
blood pressure drops
consciousness dims
the body goes still
β-endorphin floods to numb pain
this is the ancient defense
older than fear older than fight
playing dead until the danger passes
infants and toddlers can enter dorsal vagal shutdown during extreme distress or neglect

HEART RATE VARIABILITY

HRV is the variation in time between successive heartbeats measured in milliseconds
high HRV indicates strong vagal tone and parasympathetic dominance
the heart speeds on inhalation sympathetic and slows on exhalation parasympathetic
this respiratory sinus arrhythmia is a sign of healthy autonomic flexibility
high HRV correlates with emotional regulation social engagement and resilience
low HRV indicates sympathetic dominance autonomic rigidity and poor emotional regulation
HRV is measurable and it is one of the best biomarkers of physiological wellbeing

SENSATION safe | "my body is settled. I can breathe. I can listen. I can connect."
SENSATION mobilized | "my body is ready. heart pounding, muscles tight, eyes wide."
SENSATION frozen | "I can't move. I can't think. everything is far away."
SENSATION transitioning | "I'm shifting between states. my body is adjusting."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "my systems are fighting each other. sympathetic and parasympathetic both firing."

pulse autonomic_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        sympathetic and parasympathetic systems
        run simultaneously
        always
        the balance between them
        determines the body's state

    when safety is felt:
        ventral vagal dominates
        myelinated vagal fibers from nucleus ambiguus slow the heart via M₂ at SA node
        heart rate is low and variable
        respiratory sinus arrhythmia is strong
        the face opens via facial nerve CN VII
        the voice is warm via vagal laryngeal branches
        listening is easy via stapedius muscle tensioning middle ear ossicles
        this is social engagement
        this is where bonding happens

    when danger is sensed:
        the amygdala fires
        sympathetic activation through IML and sympathetic chain
        NE floods target organs via postganglionic fibers
        adrenaline floods from adrenal medulla
        heart accelerates via β₁
        breathing quickens
        digestion stops via α₂
        muscles prepare via β₂ vasodilation
        social engagement shuts down
        the body becomes a weapon or an escape vehicle

    when all escape fails:
        dorsal vagal activates
        unmyelinated vagal fibers from dorsal motor nucleus fire
        heart rate drops bradycardia
        consciousness dims
        the body goes still
        β-endorphin floods to numb
        this is the ancient defense
        older than fear
        older than fight
        playing dead until the danger passes
